Anthrax, Lesotho
-----------------
Information received on 19 Mar 2014 from Mrs Marosi Molomo, Director of Livestock Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Food Security, Department of Livestock Services, Maseru, Lesotho

Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 26 Feb 2014
Date of pre-confirmation of the event: 26 Feb 2014
Report date: 19 Mar 2014
Date submitted to OIE: 19 Mar 2014
Reason for notification: Reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: June 2013
Manifestation of disease Clinical disease
Causal agent: _Bacillus anthracis_
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, Laboratory (basic)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (1)
Outbreak 1: Berea, Hasiloane
Date of start of the outbreak: 26 Feb 2014
Outbreak status: Resolved (6 Mar 2014)
Epidemiological unit: Farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 500 / 4 / 4 / 0 / 0
Equidae / na / na / 1 / 0 / 0
Affected population: One horse and 4 cattle died suddenly.

Summary of outbreaks: Total outbreaks: 1
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 500 / 4 / 4 / 0 / 0
Equidae / na / na / 1 / 0 / 0

Outbreak statistics:
Species / Apparent morbidity rate / Apparent mortality rate / Apparent case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / 0.80 percent / 0.80 percent / 100.00 percent / 0.80 percent
Equidae**

*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter
**Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology:
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive

Control measures:
Measures applied:

Vaccination in response to the outbreak(s):
Administrative division / Species / Total Vaccinated / Details
Berea / Cattle / 757 / [no details given]

Disinfection of infected premises/establishment(s)
No treatment of affected animals

Measures to be applied: No other measures

Future Reporting: The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[Go to link to see a map of outbreak locations.]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Outbreak reporting from Lesotho is erratic, but an outbreak involving Berea cattle was reported in 2009, and a mixed series of 4 Berea outbreaks in 2012 involving 7 dogs, 10 horses, and 27 cattle.

Berea is on the western border with South Africa, and the outbreak is near the town of Peka on the following map:
http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/africa/lesotho.gif. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2342817,178.]
